!! Inspecting Widget Scope with MCP Tools

This document describes the step-by-step data flow for determining all variables visible to a specific widget in rendered wikitext, using the TiddlyWiki MCP server tools.

[img width=720 [MCP Inspect Scope Data Flow Diagram.svg]]

!! Overview

The goal is to answer: "What variables does a given widget see at render time?" This requires four tools used in sequence:

# `get_tiddler` — retrieve the tiddler source text
# `inspect_tree` — understand the widget tree structure
# `inspect_pos` — map rendered elements to source positions
# `inspect_scope` — retrieve all variables at a given position

!! Worked Example

The example uses three tiddlers:

''Tiddler `aaa`:''

```
<$let asdf=asdf>

<$link to=<<testXXX>>/>
</$let>

<$link to=<<testXXX>>/>

{{note-tiddler}}
```

''Tiddler `note-tiddler`:''

```
<<.note """This is a test""">>
```

''Tiddler `global-test-function`'' (tagged `$:/tags/Global`):

```
\function testXXX() [<asdf>!is[blank]else[xx]]
```

This setup demonstrates three important patterns:

* `<<testXXX>>` — a global function referenced via variable attribute
* `{{note-tiddler}}` — a tiddler transclusion
* `<<.note>>` — a global procedure call (inside the transcluded tiddler)

The goal is to find all variables visible to the ''first'' `<$link>` widget.

!!! Step 1: Retrieve the Tiddler

''Tool:'' `get_tiddler`<br>
''Parameters:'' `title="aaa"`, `detailed=true`<br>
''Purpose:'' Obtain the full source text of the tiddler, including any pragma definitions.

''What we learn:''

* There are two `<$link>` widgets referencing `<<testXXX>>` — one inside a `<$let>` block, one outside
* The `<$let>` block sets `asdf=asdf`
* A `{{note-tiddler}}` transclusion at the bottom
* `testXXX` is not defined locally — it must be a global

!!! Step 2: Inspect the Widget Tree

''Tool:'' `inspect_tree`<br>
''Parameters:'' `text=<tiddler text>`, `context="aaa"`, `depth=5`<br>
''Purpose:'' Get a structural overview of the rendered widget tree — how many nodes, what types, and what link targets exist.

''Result:''

```
Total: 12 nodes (full tree)
Types: 3 text, 2 let, 2 element, 2 link, 1 widget, 1 importvariables, 1 set
Links (2): asdf, xx
```

''What we learn:''

* There are 2 link widgets in the tree
* The first link resolves to `asdf` (because `<$let asdf=asdf>` is in scope, so `<<testXXX>>` evaluates using `asdf`)
* The second link resolves to `xx` (the fallback, since `asdf` variable is not in scope outside the `<$let>` block)

!!! Step 3: Get the Position Map

''Tool:'' `inspect_pos`<br>
''Parameters:'' `text=<tiddler text>`, `context="aaa"`<br>
''Purpose:'' Render the wikitext to HTML with compact `p=` position attributes and a title index header. These positions are file-ready line numbers.

''Result:''

```html
[0=aaa]
<p p="0:9-10">
  <a class="tc-tiddlylink tc-tiddlylink-missing"
     p="0:9" href="#asdf">asdf</a>
</p>
<p p="0:12">
  <a class="tc-tiddlylink tc-tiddlylink-missing"
     p="0:12" href="#xx">xx</a>
</p>
```

''What we learn:''

* The title index `[0=aaa]` maps index 0 to tiddler `aaa`
* The first link is at position `p="0:9"` — line 9 of `aaa`, inside the `<$let>` block
* The second link is at position `p="0:12"` — line 12 of `aaa`, outside the `<$let>` block
* The position values are file-ready line numbers (accounting for the .tid file header)
* The `charPos` needed for `inspect_scope` is derived from the source position within the text field

!!! Step 4: Inspect the Scope

''Tool:'' `inspect_scope`<br>
''Parameters:'' `tiddler="aaa"`, `charPos=18`<br>
''Purpose:'' Find the widget at the given character position and return the variables in its scope.

''Default output'' (local scope + used globals):

```
Scope at char 18 (widget: link, distance: 0, 244 vars)

— local scope
var asdf = asdf
var currentTiddler = aaa

— used globals
fn testXXX() @global-test-function

+241 globals (use all:true to see all, or filter to narrow)
```

''Key fields in the header:''

|!Field |!Meaning |
|`widget: link` |The closest widget at this position is a `link` widget |
|`distance: 0` |Exact match — the charPos landed directly on this widget |
|`244 vars` |Total number of variables visible at this point in the tree |

!! Output Sections

`inspect_scope` organises its output into three sections:

!!! 1. Local scope

Variables defined without a `sourceTitle` — these are set by widgets in the current tiddler or by the rendering context:

* `<$let>`, `<$set>`, `<$vars>` bindings
* `\function`, `\define`, `\procedure` pragmas within the tiddler
* Context variables like `currentTiddler`, `thisTiddler`

!!! 2. Used globals

Imported variables (with a `sourceTitle`) that are ''actually referenced'' somewhere in the tiddler. Detection works by:

# Scanning the entire tiddler's parse tree for variable references — `<<macro>>` calls, `<$widget $variable=.../>` transclude nodes, and `type: "macro"` attributes (`to=<<varname>>`)
# Recursively following the chain — if a used variable's body contains `<varname>` filter references or `<<macro>>` calls, those are marked as used too

This means a global function like `testXXX` shows up as "used" even when inspecting a widget that doesn't directly reference it, because it's used elsewhere in the same tiddler.

!!! 3. Other globals (all:true only)

The remaining imported variables from core modules and the current edition. Only shown when `all:true` is set.

!! Variable Type Prefixes

The scope output prefixes each variable with its type:

|!Prefix |!Meaning |!Example |
|`var` |Simple variable (`<$let>`, `<$set>`, `<$vars>`) |`var asdf = asdf` |
|`fn` |Function (`\function` pragma) |`fn testXXX()` |
|`proc` |Procedure (`\procedure` pragma) |`proc tag-picker(...)` |
|`macro` |Macro (`\define` or legacy macro) |`macro tabs(...)` |
|`def` |Definition (general `\define` with params) |`def timeline(...)` |
|`widget` |Custom widget definition |`widget $expand.able(...)` |

!! Position Mapping: `p=` to `charPos`

The `inspect_pos` tool returns line numbers relative to the ''.tid file'' (including the header). The `inspect_scope` tool requires a `charPos` — a character offset within the tiddler's ''text field'' (excluding the header). The `tiddler` parameter on `inspect_scope` handles this conversion when you provide a tiddler title directly.

''Tip:'' For best results, use `charPos` values that land directly on a widget start tag (e.g., the `<` of `<$link`). The `distance: 0` in the output confirms an exact hit. If the distance is large, the scope may belong to a parent or sibling widget.

!! Render Context

By default, `inspect_scope` renders the tiddler in isolation — just the wikitext with `currentTiddler` set. In the browser, tiddlers are rendered inside a deep widget chain (PageTemplate → navigator → story list → ViewTemplate → body) that sets many additional variables.

The `renderContext` parameter lets you simulate these additional layers:

!!! `"isolated"` (default)

Renders only the tiddler text with `currentTiddler` set. This is the fastest and simplest mode.

''Local variables visible:'' only what the tiddler itself defines plus `currentTiddler`.

!!! `"viewtemplate"`

Adds the variables that the ViewTemplate sets when displaying a tiddler in the story river:

|!Variable |!Value |!Set by |
|`storyTiddler` |the tiddler title |ViewTemplate `<$vars>` |
|`tiddlerInfoState` |`$:/state/popup/tiddler-info--{title}` |ViewTemplate `<$vars>` |
|`folded-state` |`$:/state/folded/{title}` |ViewTemplate macro |

!!! `"root"`

Adds everything from `"viewtemplate"` plus the full UI chain variables:

|!Variable |!Value |!Set by |
|`tv-story-list` |`$:/StoryList` |Navigator widget |
|`tv-history-list` |`$:/HistoryList` |Navigator widget |
|`tv-config-toolbar-icons` |from `$:/config/Toolbar/Icons` |PageTemplate `<$vars>` |
|`tv-config-toolbar-text` |from `$:/config/Toolbar/Text` |PageTemplate `<$vars>` |
|`tv-config-toolbar-class` |from `$:/config/Toolbar/ButtonClass` |PageTemplate `<$vars>` |
|`tv-enable-drag-and-drop` |from `$:/config/DragAndDrop/Enable` |PageTemplate `<$vars>` |
|`tv-show-missing-links` |from `$:/config/MissingLinks` |PageTemplate `<$vars>` |
|`storyviewTitle` |from `$:/view` |PageTemplate `<$vars>` |
|`languageTitle` |from `$:/language` |PageTemplate `<$vars>` |

This most closely matches what the browser's variable inspector shows.

!! Scope Inheritance

Variables are inherited through the widget tree:

# ''Widget bindings'' (`<$let>`, `<$set>`, `<$vars>`) — available only within the widget's subtree
# ''Pragma definitions'' (`\function`, `\define`, `\procedure`) — available throughout the tiddler
# ''Global imports'' — macros and procedures from core modules and the current edition, available everywhere

This is why the first link sees `asdf` (it is inside `<$let asdf=asdf>`) but the second link does not (it is outside that block).

!! Comparison: First Link vs Second Link

|!Aspect |!First Link (charPos=18) |!Second Link (charPos=51) |
|Local `asdf` |`asdf` (from `<$let>`) |//not in scope// |
|`testXXX` |used global @global-test-function |used global @global-test-function |
|`currentTiddler` |`aaa` |`aaa` |

Both links see the same used globals (tiddler-wide detection), but only the first link has `asdf` in its local scope.

!! Cross-Tiddler Transclusion

The tiddler `aaa` transcludes `note-tiddler` via `{{note-tiddler}}`. To inspect variables inside the transcluded content, use `inspect_scope` with `tiddler="note-tiddler"`:

```
Scope at char 0 (widget: text, distance: 0, 251 vars)

— local scope
var thisTiddler = note-tiddler
var text = This is a test
var title = Note
var icon = $:/core/images/info-button
var class = doc-note
var iconSize = 22pt
var _ = This is a test
var currentTiddler = note-tiddler

— used globals
proc .note(_, title:Note, ...) @$:/editions/tw5.com/doc-macros
```

The local scope shows the `.note` procedure's parameters resolved to their values. The `thisTiddler` is set to `note-tiddler` because that's the tiddler being rendered.

!! Browser vs MCP: Key Differences

The browser's variable inspector and the MCP server's `inspect_scope` may show different results for the same widget position. These differences are expected and stem from how each renders the tiddler.

!!! 1. Rendering context

The browser renders tiddlers inside the full UI widget chain (PageTemplate → navigator → story list → ViewTemplate → body). The MCP server renders in isolation by default. Use the `renderContext` parameter (`"viewtemplate"` or `"root"`) to simulate the browser's context.

|!Variable |!Browser |!MCP (isolated) |!MCP (root) |
|`currentTiddler` |yes |yes |yes |
|`storyTiddler` |yes |no |yes |
|`tiddlerInfoState` |yes |no |yes |
|`tv-story-list` |yes |no |yes |
|`tv-config-toolbar-icons` |yes |no |yes |

!!! 2. Transclusion context

In the browser, when `aaa` transcludes `note-tiddler` via `{{note-tiddler}}`, the TranscludeWidget wraps the content and sets a `transclusion` variable (e.g. `{note-tiddler|note-tiddler|||}`). The MCP server renders `note-tiddler` directly without this wrapper, so `transclusion` is not set.

This is a fundamental limitation: `inspect_scope` renders a single tiddler — it does not replicate the transclusion chain from a parent tiddler.

!!! 3. Variable count

The browser typically shows more variables (~260+) than the MCP server in isolated mode (~244) because of the UI chain variables. Using `renderContext="root"` brings the count closer (~256).

!! Parameters Reference

|!Parameter |!Type |!Default |!Description |
|`tiddler` |string | |Tiddler title to render |
|`charPos` |number |0 |Character position within the text field |
|`text` |string | |Wikitext to render instead of a tiddler |
|`context` |string | |Context tiddler (sets `currentTiddler`) |
|`match` |object | |Match widget by variable values to disambiguate |
|`filter` |string | |Only show variables matching this substring |
|`all` |boolean |false |Show all variables including unused globals |
|`renderContext` |string |`"isolated"` |Widget tree context: `"isolated"`, `"viewtemplate"`, or `"root"` |

!! AI Agent Test Prompt

Use this prompt to test the MCP server inspect_scope data flow in a fresh conversation. It ensures only MCP tool output is used, with no trained knowledge:

```
I want to test the MCP server tools only. Rules for this conversation:

1. Only show information returned by MCP server tools — no info from training data or conversation context
2. Show the exact tool calls you make and the data flow between them
3. Do not augment, interpret, or add context beyond what the tools return

The tiddler `aaa` has some widgets that reference variables. Using only MCP tools:

1. Get the tiddler source
2. Inspect the widget tree
3. Get the position map
4. Run `inspect_scope` at the first widget that references a variable — show default output (local + used globals)
5. Run `inspect_scope` again with `all:true` at the same position
6. Compare the two outputs

Any questions before you start?
```
